Reigning East Africa University Games men&rsquo;s volleyball holders Kenyatta University shared spoils with Jomo Kenyatta University of Agriculture and Technology to continue leading the KUSA Nairobi North Conference.Though JKUAT got the win, they took home two points as KU grabbed one from their sole fixture over the weekend to top the league with 20 points. Unbeaten St. Paul&rsquo;s University are second with 20 points too, but have two matches in hand, while JKUAT is third with 18. The match that lasted two hours and 13 minutes saw JKUAT beat KU 3-2 to narrow the three-point gap between them and league leaders to two. This time without the services of Kenya&rsquo;s best setter and Kenya Prisons&rsquo; Kevin Maiyo, KU started the game on a high note but faltered and let JKUAT run away with the first set 23-25.In a tightly contested second set, KU regrouped and put up spirited fight to garner a 25-21 win to level the scores 1-1. Tutored by Gilbert Kibet, KU had a field day in the third set as JKUAT surrendered after amassing 16 points only (25-16). Trailing KU 2-1 sets, the &lsquo;rained on lion&rsquo; staged a gallant fight against the regional varsity holders and hammered them 29-31, extending the game to a rally set. Second-placed St. Paul&rsquo;s University handed Mt. Kenya University, who also compete in the Kenya Volleyball Federation&rsquo;s national league a 3-0 beating in sets of 25-19, 25-22, 25-14 to continue with their winning ways. Kenya College of Accountancy University defeated a once lethal Daystar University 3-0 (25-21, 25-12, 25-20), whereas Gretsa clobbered KU Ruiru Campus 3-0 (26-24, 25-17, 27-25).In the women&rsquo;s category, all matches ended in identical 3-0 set score-line. KCAU lost to both USIU-Africa 25-19,25-16,25-16) and KU (25-07, 25-16, 25-15). KU also succumbed to St. Paul&rsquo;s as the once lethal Daystar University fell to Mt. Kenya.